With these existential challenges looming over us, we propose three changes to policy-relevant IR scholarship: (1) rescoping political possibilities; (2) adjudicating the debate between malevolence and failure of imagination; and (3) reassessing the meaning of policy relevance.

We identify two common claims of impossibility around structural obstacles and adversarial forces and explain why those are unsatisfactory. Next, we explore what this means for the good faith assumption, commonly ascribed to policymakers in these domains.

Building on the insight that crises do not just  reconfigure the current political landscape, but that they can also help us to re-examine the past, we identify a gap between what policymakers promised they would do and what they did to address climate change and nuclear danger.

@NHMU has an exhibit coming out in fall of 2023 called "A Climate of Hope." This exhibit will focus on the effects climate change will have locally, and build a sense of community that not only feels responsible for our future but proud to lead those changes. 13/15

I could bring up so many different organizations that are working to prevent drastic climate change, but I want to focus on one that is local, one that gives back to our community, and one that I hold a deep personal connection to. 12/15

Email your representatives and express your concern about these topics. Show that it shouldn't be a partisan issue. Vote for candidates who support responsible policies on climate change. Support local efforts to mitigate negative climate consequences. Be loud. 11/15

So what can we do? So many of these threads end in asking you to do small things like conserving your water use or recycling, but that isn't what is going to make these changes. We have to take more radical action and put pressure on those responsible. 10/15

Utah's heat will result in more fires and more extremely hot days. Today, we experience about 20 extremely hot days (days that surpass the top 1% on record) per year. By 2050, that number will be doubled. 9/15

Agriculture will take a massive hit as well. Hotter weather means less water for crops, drier soil, and loss of livestock. Agriculture in Utah accounts for almost 5% of Utah's economy, but it uses almost 80% of our available water. 8/15

The lake and the ecosystems dependent on it are predicted to collapse in as soon as five years, causing massive toxic dust storms in the Salt Lake Valley area, loss of wildlife, and billions of dollars in annual damages. When we say the situation here is drastic, we mean it. 7/15 https://t.co/Y2Ppe2fQJ5

It's not just our drinking water that's affected either. The Great Salt Lake has experienced record lows in the past few years. These lows have exposed hundreds of square miles of toxic chemicals like mercury, arsenic, and selenium that resided at the bottom of the lake. 6/15 https://t.co/zsCspCRO27

These extreme decreases will skyrocket the duration of our droughts, and affect millions of people. The economic effects are dire as well, considering that 6% of jobs in the state are supported by tourism, which is dependent on proper environmental conditions. 5/15 https://t.co/fY8Fvt22At

let's focus on this first problem for now. Utah gets much of its water from the Colorado river and snowmelt from the Wasatch mountains. In the coming years, we will see more rain than snow and a 20-30% decrease in colorado river flow. 4/15

Currently, our biggest climate threats are heat and drought. With temperatures expected to rise 3 degrees by 2050, our already frequent droughts will increase in intensity and frequency in the coming years, resulting in less water, fewer crops, and hotter days. 3/15 https://t.co/ZpKIYXIXLv

Super glad I get to share this project with y'all! Since this is technically for my climate change class I won't be discussing the numerous other problems that Utah faces politically, despite the fact that they are equally important :) 2/15
